segments.text: Everyone was already ready to go, strapped in vests and accompanying gear.
Their personal weapons crossed over their chests, faces smeared with camel paint.
Dan, the company commander, passed by her on his way to them.
For a moment, their gazes met, and she shyly mumbled, good luck.
Not even sure he heard.
Until she heard him reply, thank you, with deep seriousness.
She stood there for long minutes, watching them move away, knowing she wouldn't find peace until they returned.
Suddenly the battalion commander was beside her, quietly saying they'll be fine, and by morning the operation will be behind us.
He recalled the day he made her a temporary operations sergeant, due to the operations officer's illness requiring prolonged absence.
She was a personnel and welfare officer, always ready to help wherever needed, often in the operations department.
She was serious, responsible, and gradually grew aware of everything happening.
He asked her how she was with navigation, and she half smiled, saying it was her best grade in the course.
As a child, she had roamed the dunes for days and always knew how to return home safely.
Good, he have smiled.
That was rhetorical.
I checked your file.
Look, I want to add a role for you.
You'll temporarily also be the operation sergeant.
When things calm down, I'll send you for a short training.
But even without it, I'm sure you'll succeed.
From this moment, you have permission to approach me with anything unclear.
She was a bit shocked, but also thrilled because she felt appreciated.
She was deeply involved in the soldiers' lives, but sometimes wasn't needed much, and always helped with operational issues in busy moments on top of her official duties.
She was aware of everything, like the battalion commander, knowing any new operations officer would take months to learn what she already knew.
She had much sympathy for him as a person.
He was not what one might expect from the commander of an elite unit.
A bit of gray in his hair, he was tall and a bit awkward, with sun and worry lines on his forehead and at his eyes' corners.
But beyond all, there was something warm and human in him.
He knew every problem of every soldier, asked after families, sent her on home visits with a jeep full of food, ensuring the soldier's hearts were at peace.
Shortly after notifying her of her new role, while she was excited in his office, he called Dan.
Meet, he said with a smile.
This is our new operation, Sergeant.
If there's anything you can teach or explain, find time to do it.
Beyond that, she already knows everything.
Even if Dan was surprised, he didn't let her feel it.
He smiled nicely and wished her success.
She rose hesitantly and smiled awkwardly.
I'll do my best, she said.
Before closing the door, she turned, saw them watching her, looked at the battalion commander, and said, Thank you.
That was four months earlier.
Since then, there had been endless operations, including small but significant surgical actions.
Some were talked about in the media.
Others wouldn't be discussed for years.
She was engrossed in her work with deep understanding and did her best.
She was very attached to the soldiers.
Even before her appointment, she was involved in their personal affairs as part of her role.
But now, involved with life and death issues, she was twice as anxious for them every departure and relieved when they returned safely.
If someone was injured, it was she who visited the family, knowing the unit was like a warm operational family.
But this was the partly untrue story she told herself, as if she deliberately deceived those around her.
She knew everything about her soldiers, yet they knew nothing about her.
She guarded her privacy strictly, sharing nothing, not wanting to be categorized as a soldier with difficulties at home.
she felt capable of handling her issues alone.
Only once, when heading home for the weekend, did the battalion commander say, well, mom must be waiting with the Shabbat dishes.
Caught off guard, she looked up in embarrassment and suddenly, out of nowhere, it came out.
My mom hasn't been with us for years.
It's just dad and me.
But it's fine.
Shabbat Shalom, she added, and left before tear surfaced and he could react.
How could she tell?
Im, it was just her.
The last raid lasted almost a whole day beyond plan due to complications.
At times communication fell silent and she felt choked by worry and concern.
The battalion commander paced the room and she tried to reassure them both.
They'll be fine.
Their experts know the job better than anyone.
Eventually, the soldiers made contact.
They're on their way back, he told her.
Everyone's fine.
He saw the relief in her eyes.
A remarkable girl, he thought.
Barely 19, but so mature for her age.
On Thursday afternoon, she prepared to go home.
She stood at the bus stop on the deserted road in the Negev, waiting for the bus.
Suddenly, a jeep emerged from the base gate, approached her, and stopped.
It was Dan, the company commander.
Can I help?
Where are you headed?
She knew his parents' home was in Moshov Bayt Yanai, and replied accordingly.
We'll ride with you to the Ashkelon Junction.
Thanks.
She placed her bag on the back seat, sat beside him, and they set off.
It was the first time she left the base not on a rattling bus.
Delighted that the journey would be shorter and bring her home early.
They exchanged polite words, not much beyond.
She felt no immediate connection with him.
He was somewhat closed, focused on the heavy task he carried.
She heard him joke with the guys, but not in the operations room, where there was always a sacred operational atmosphere.
Dan drove fast, but carefully.
She didn't dare break the silence or close her eyes to nap.
Just looked ahead on the road.
After about half an hour, she felt him slow.
The jeep swaying slightly.
She immediately realized fatigue was overtaking him and called out, Dan.
He recovered and smiled sheepishly.
Sorry, I'm just dead tired.
15 minutes later, it happened again.
and they almost veered into a roadside ditch.
But with instinctive reflex, she reached for the wheel and steered it left.
He looked at her apologetically, and she quietly asked him to stop, switch seats, and move to the driver's seat.
He didn't argue, recline the passenger seat slightly, closed his eyes and was in dreamland within seconds.
Now she steered the Jeep like she did her life, holding both tightly.
She didn't stop at the city entrance, but continued to the parking spot at the entrance of the pink house.
Dan still slept like a log.
She left him sleeping in the Jeep.
Open the house door.
Took a sheet of paper and a pen and wrote largely.
When you wake, enter through the door, open to your left.
He knew nothing about her, and she realized she was completely caught, but it was too late to regret.
Two hours later, everything was clean.
Chairs stacked on tables in the dining room.
The floor still damp from mopping, something already cooking on the stove to quell the hunger rising in her.
Between tasks, she'd peek at him.
He slept so deeply.
No wonder!
With his accumulated lack of sleep, he could sleep like this for a week.
At some point, after cleaning the rooms, she pulled a thin blanket, covered him, and returned to the dining room.
Until the floor dried and the dish on the stove was ready, she sat at the piano.

Just as she was, barefoot, in her short pants and an old tank top, her long braid behind, hair slightly tousled in front, playing quietly, afraid the sounds might drift through open windows and wake him.
This instrument was and remained her great solace, calming, comforting, and conciliatory.
Her heart poured out with each touch of the keys.
Now she was with Frank Sinatra's When I Was Seventeen, softly.
Suddenly she thought that Seventeen wasn't so long ago.
Her fingers flew over the keys.
She was completely immersed in playing, not noticing he stood beside her, watching with amazement.
Suddenly he was close beside her.
And she abruptly removed her fingers from the piano and stammered in embarrassment.
Good morning.
Dan stood rooted, mouth agape, in his military pants, but only with a white t-shirt tucked in.
Barefoot as well, apparently having taken his shoes off in the jeep.
His hair was slightly tousled, eyes red, looking at her with deep seriousness, asking, who are you?
What is this place?
And what's that wonderful smell driving me crazy?
She burst into a liberating, a childish laugh.
He couldn't recall ever hearing her laugh.
Apparently, here, at home, with her music, she was completely free.
He looked at her, realizing he hadn't really seen her until now.
The slim figure of a girl, eyes with deep blue inviting a dive.
How hadn't he seen she was so beautiful?
She always wore the slightly loose army uniform, as if trying to hide within.
with the ponytail or braid and without any adornments.
He was only aware of her seriousness and that human warmth that led the soldiers to share all their troubles with her.
But now he saw an almost unfamiliar girl, or rather, another one.
She laughed out loud at his amazement.
Come, there's an empty room.
Take a shower, change clothes, then eat, and you can go."
She entered behind the wall by the pretty wooden bar, returned with towels in her arms, led him to the room's area, opened a room smelling pleasantly of cleanliness, handed him the towels, and left.
She set the table for three, used to someone joining immediately upon realizing she was there.
She was a little worried, unsure of what she did was allowed under military law, considering she worked without permission during her service.
She tried calming herself by thinking that since it was also her home, it could be a mitigating circumstance.
But really, it wasn't her home, only temporarily.
But even without that, she understood she was completely exposed and would have no choice but to explain at least some things.
She didn't know how it would be received.
The house ran almost by itself during the week, with several regular tenants working nearby, graced by her care on her weekend visits.
Her father still lived with his partner in Tel Aviv.
They'd see each other occasionally when he visited on weekends.
It didn't mar their love, roles merely reversed lately.
She somewhat raised him and became the responsible adult for a while.
She embraced Yahuda's consent to maintain the house just for now, not ready to give up her pink house despite all the challenges.
She clung to it with all her strength, managing bills, clearing debts, making payments, cleaning, organizing, even tending its garden.
She knew eventually she'd have no choice but to let go.
But not yet.
As long as it was possible, she had a home.
Only sometimes.
When she wasn't on guard, did terrible sense of loneliness seep in, threatening to shatter the walls she'd built around herself.
In those moments, she'd curl up deeply in the corner armchair, simply waiting for it to pass.
She entered her room, and after washing, changed into long jeans and a white T-shirt, somehow feeling slightly exposed to him in her short trousers and tank top.
She brushed her hair, braided it anew, but remained barefoot, unwilling to give that up.
Turning to the dining room, she entered the kitchen, turned off the heat under the pot, placed a towel on the rice pot to keep it warm and left.
It was getting dark, and she turned on some surrounding lights.
The yellow light highlighted Yosef's paintings on the walls.
She loved them.
They enveloped her with his presence, even though he was far away.
And there was the stunning portrait of her mother, painted by Yosef, when he first met her in her youth.
She hung it on the wall by the bar, passing it every time she entered the kitchen or went behind the bar.
Sometimes in a burst of emotion, she'd waved to her mother, saying, hey mom, it made her feel good.
Thus, though entirely alone, both were always with her.
He, who left his paintings behind, and she, whose eyes in the portrait gazed deeply into her daughter's eyes.
When he returned from his shower, Dan wore exactly like her, long jeans and a clean white t-shirt.
Incredibly also barefoot.
His hair still damp, his dark curls slightly tousled, giving him a somewhat mischievous look.
I see we stayed in uniform, he smiled at her.
Yeah, she smiled back.
And above all, barefoot.
Come, sit, I'll bring the food.
She entered the kitchen, and when she returned with two loaded plates, she found the doctor standing by the table, shaking dans.
Hand, I'm a friend from the Army, Dan said, and she smiled to herself at the new definition, placed the plates on the table, and was gathered into the doctor's warm embrace.
Hello girl, so good you're here to feed all the hungry.
I assume the third seat is set for me.
Yes, she said, I cleaned your room and realized you were here because of the razor and book by the bed.
I assumed you'd come to eat following the smell.
He didn't sit down, just move behind the bar.
Cold out a wine bottle he had brought the previous week and three glasses, then join the table.
He poured wine for them, raised his glass, and said, as was his habit, to the prettiest girl in the kindergarten.
Leora noticed the growing surprise of the commander.
They began a pleasant exploratory chat from the book the doctor was reading to the shared love for animals.
It turned out the commander had a pair of horses and a dog at home.
The doctor told Dan that he had been the groom for the French vacation village for two years and brought Leora his horse for winter so it wouldn't suffer from the storms and cold near the sea.
So for at least three months each winter, she had her own private horse.
Then, as if in passing, the doctor suddenly said, I also served in the unit.
She was completely surprised.
She had no idea about that.
She only knew he studied veterinary medicine abroad.
Never bothered to ask him what he did in the army.
From that moment, they almost forgot her presence, sinking into checking old commander's identities and covert operations.
She removed the dishes from the table and returned with black coffee for them to drink after the wine bottle, which had been mostly consumed by the two.
She didn't feel comfortable rushing him.
He seemed so relaxed, as if all his tensions and burdens of responsibility had been washed away with the wine and pleasant company.
She heard him tell the doctor how she drove him there because he had fallen asleep at the wheel, almost sending them into a ditch, and she gasped.
If anyone knew she didn't have a driver's license, it was the doctor.
He taught her to drive his small sports car in the large parking lot by the beach.
She had pleaded with him so much that he had no choice.
Once or twice a week, before she even turned 17, he'd let her drive there, explaining all he could about driving, watching her gradually become a skilled parking lot driver.
The doctor cast her a reproachful glance but said nothing.
When she rose to clear the table, he joined her.
She washed dishes, and he stood with a towel in hand.
It's not funny, he scolded her.
If they had caught you on the road, you could have gone to jail.
It would have been less funny if we had found ourselves in a ditch, she retorted.
What choice did I have?
Besides, you say I drive excellently.
I had an excellent teacher, she flattered, hoping to make him smile.
Suddenly, she saw Dan standing in the kitchen entrance.
She had no idea how much he had heard.
I also know how to dry dishes," he said as if he hadn't heard a thing, taking a towel and a plate, drying it and placing it on the nearby shelf.
So stood the doctor, the driving teacher and the commander, the army friend, drying the dishes she washed.
Honestly, suddenly said the commander, I'd love to stay here and leave only in the morning.
If the room's available, I'd be happy to rent it and have a good night's sleep.
She looked at him in surprise.
Why hadn't she thought of it?
Maybe she should have offered it herself.
After all, without realizing it was almost ten.
Why rent it?
It's available, and you're welcome to stay.
On second thought, I'll sleep better knowing you're not sailing the road looking for a ditch to settle in.
She smiled, handed him the key again, and said to them both, Go to sleep.
I'll close up soon.
Good night.
Blessed silence wrapped the place.
She remained alone, turning off the lights, guiding the house to sleep gradually.
Only the lamp above the corner armchair stayed on.
She settled into it, legs tucked beneath, reached for the book waiting from last.
Weak and was immediately absorbed, detached from everything happening around.
When she lifted her eyes from the book, it was almost midnight.
She rose forcefully from the armchair, said goodnight to her mom's portrait, turned off the light, locked the door, and made the twenty steps to the dark room area.
where only the standing lamp at its center lit her way.
